Analysis
As concurrent users increased from 10 to 100, mean response time per request rose from 0.845 ms to 8.613 ms, and
the total time to complete all requests grew from 0.008s to 0.086s. This is expected — more concurrent connections
mean more contention for the same single-core t2.micro CPU.
Throughput (requests/sec) stayed consistently high across all three tests (roughly 9,700–11,800 req/sec), showing the
server handles both light and heavy simulated traffic well for a static HTML page served by Nginx. Interestingly, Test 2
had slightly lower throughput than Test 3 — likely test-to-test variance from background CPU noise rather than a true
bottleneck, since Test 3 (the heaviest test) still performed strongly.
Zero failed requests across all three tests confirms Nginx’s stability on the t2.micro instance for this workload, and that
no connections were dropped even at 100 concurrent users.
CloudWatch monitoring during Test 3 showed a visible CPU spike coinciding with the load test window, confirming the
monitoring pipeline correctly reflects real load in near real time — while also confirming CPU usage stayed comfortably
under the 70% alarm threshold.
Bottlenecks and recommended optimizations
Single vCPU limit: t2.micro has only 1 vCPU and burstable CPU credits — under sustained (not just short-burst)
high concurrency, response time would degrade further once burst credits are exhausted.
Single point of failure: all traffic goes to one EC2 instance — no failover if it goes down.
Recommended for production:
Add an Application Load Balancer with an Auto Scaling Group across multiple instances/AZs, so traffic is
distributed and capacity scales with demand.
Move to a larger instance type or enable unlimited CPU credit mode if sustained high load is expected.
Add a CDN (e.g. CloudFront) in front of static content to reduce direct load on EC2.


